SYMPTOM_TEXT: Received the first dose of Moderna vaccine at 11 a.m. March 15. About 8 p.m. March 15 started feeling tired with chills. About midnight March 16 severe chills, restlessness, headache, muscle aches, nauseous and fever of 101.  Took two extra-strength Tylenol. 3 a.m. fever broke with sweats. Headache and body ache remained, as did chills. Took two Advil when I woke up about 7 a.m. on  March 16 for a headache. But I was too tired and achy to get out of bed. The fever came back to 102 degrees. Nauseous, couldn't eat much. Headache. At 2:30 p.m. on March 16, I felt better...  I was very tired the night of March 16 and still had a minor headache and went to bed about  8 p.m. On March 17, I was back to normal with only a very minor headache and some diahreaha that morning and afternoon.  I did not take any medicine that day. On March 18 I had no symptoms at all. I am a very healthy 42-year-old adult. I would classify my reaction as significant, but not severe. I called in sick to work (and I work from home). So it was enough to take me out of a day.

I got the first COVID vaccine on March 8th. The next day, I  had a rash on my chest and thighs that became hives. The hives were hot and itchy. This reaction gradually grew worse and the rash spread to the rest of my legs, down my arms, and to my belly.  When it started up my neck, I noticed that my throat was getting a bit sore and tight. I called my primary care provider and she told me to go to the ER.  The ER providers drew blood, which was normal except for low potassium and elevated red blood cells. They treated me with IV Benadryl and steroids, which caused the symptoms to dissipate quickly. The doctor also prescribed Pepcid and an epipen.
LAB_DATA: Metabolic panel: 3/9 Low potassium, elevated red blood cells Everything else is normal
ALLERGIES: Morphine Strong reactions to bug bites and poison ivy

Treated for Neuroleptic malignant syndrome 2/2 clozapine  Uncertain if vaccine contributed to event, but recent case report published relating clozapine toxicity and Pfizer COVID vaccine, so submitting to VAERS for evaluation

78 year old man without prior DVT/PE history, who had first Moderna vaccine dose on 12/29/20 (lot 011J20A) and second Moderna vaccine dose on 02/02/21 (030L20A) (information from patient provided vaccination card) who presented to the ER on 02/20/21 with one week of subjective dyspnea and palpitations. Chest CT with bilateral pulmonary emboli. There were also groundglass opacities in the right upper lobe. Rapid test for COVID 19 on 02/20/21 was negative. Subsequent antibody testing for COVID19 on 03/01/20 (IgG, IgA. IgM) also interpreted as negative. The pulmonary embolus was considered to be unprovoked and an association with prior COVID19 vaccination is interpreted as possible but unproven. The patient was initiated on anticoagulation. Further workup for underlying thrombophilia hematological disorders is pending at this time however the current assessment remains as an unprovoked pulmonary embolus occurring 18 days after second Moderna vaccine dose. Current CT imaging without evidence of recurrent malignancy and there are no identifiable risk factors for pulmonary embolus. The physician submitting this report is a Hematologist Oncologist.
HISTORY: Gastroesophageal reflux well controlled Prostate cancer s/p prostatectomy 2010 in remission since then

Patient with past medical history significant for multiple sclerosis arrives at emergency department for concern for allergic reaction after receiving the Moderna COVID-19 vaccine 3/12/21.  Patient describes that soon after receiving the vaccine yesterday, she has felt swelling over her face and hands, and felt somewhat dizzy.  This morning, patient with shortness of breath, wheezes, continued facial swelling, abdominal pain, nausea, vomiting.  Also reports left upper and lower extremity weakness, typical of patient's recent MS flares.  911 was called, on arrival EMS administered Benadryl 25 mg, famotidine, and methylprednisolone, then transported patient to this emergency department. On arrival to this emergency department, patient describes that she is still only slightly nauseous, however patient does feel chest tightness, shortness of breath, and a strange feeling in her throat. After arriving a diagnosis of anaphylaxis on rooming of patient, IM epinephrine ordered and administered with significant improvement in shortness of breath and expected increase in heart rate.  Provided racemic epinephrine nebulizer as well.  Deferred Benadryl, steroids, histamine blockers as these have been given in route by EMS.  After these treatments as above, patient felt better, and over the next 5 hours slowly returned to baseline without any recurrence of significant shortness of breath, nausea, vomiting.  Patient discharged home  Next day, patient awoke with recurrence of facial swelling after sleeping, as well as redness, initially without chest tightness or shortness of breath, which then developed over the course of the day.  Patient states that she used her IM epinephrine approximately an hour prior to presentation due to concerns for worsening chest tightness.  Returned to emergency department.  Observed and was later discharged with steroids,  antihistamines and albuterol nebulizer.

This continued for about 3-4 minutes.  When my heart/ blood pressure seemed to go back to normal, I sat for an additional 15 minutes.   I had 3 more incidents that day of dizzy and lightheadness throughout the day but not to the extent of the initial, almost passing out, spell. Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine EUA I am experiencing intense itching and rash on torso, legs, neck, and scalp. The rash is maculopapular, but sometimes becomes inflamed and looks similar to hives. It is hot to the touch and very itchy--both of these symptoms are more intense at night. I have also observed chilblains are appearing on my fingers.  I regularly experienced chilblains from 2004-2010, but have had none since until now.  I also experienced chills, night sweats, and swollen lymph nodes. I attempted to treat the rash with triamcinolone acetone 0.1%, which was prescribed for a similar condition in the past, and OTC antihistamines, both oral and topical.  I saw my dermatologist on 3/16, who advised me to continue triamcinolone and also gave me a 40mg steroid injection. She believes the rash may be a response to my vaccine. I unfortunately have not experienced much relief yet, and the rash and intense itching continue.  The chilblains, however, are clearing.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: About 3 days after the vaccine I started feeling arm pain (right below the shoulder, not exactly at the injection site, a little back), in the evening, around suppertime. In the morning it got much worse. I had a little trip the next morning (3 hours each way) and when I returned home the pain was really severe. Used Ibuprofen at home and it solved the problem at first (for the weekend), it would take off that edge. But by Tuesday, I noticed that it was not getting any better just would ease off while taking Tylenol and Ibuprofen. Decided to go see my PCP. Initially PCP thought it was a case of tendinitis and was treated with Voltaren and Tramadol for night time in case it was too hard to sleep. Took Voltaren for a couple of days but did not see any real improvement so decided to go back to the Ibuprofen. The next Monday or Tuesday (about a week later) it was really really bad, and PCP gave me a shot of cortisone into that shoulder because at that time I was feelings numbness on my fingers and horrible pain in the shoulder. About 48/72hrs after the shot the pain subsided but the numbness and the tingling on my pointer finger and thumb were still present. The pain went away in about a week. Then PCP decided to refer me to see a neurologist. By the time I had my appt the numbness and tingling were much better and I had some tests done and they came back normal. Never lost strength in my arm. Neurologist said the numbness and tingling should go away on its own.  Now, 2 months later he numbness and tingling are really mild, I am a stomach sleeper and I can't because if I do it will make my arm tingling again. Nowadays I feel it maybe once or twice a day an not extreme.
LAB_DATA: Dr had a test done with me.

We asked if he had eaten breakfast this morning and he stated that he had a bowl of cereal. I instructed for someone to have him sit on the ground and to get him some candy  and a sugary drink.  A package of skittles was presented along with a Mountain Dew.  After finishing both the candy and Mountain Dew  (aprox 4 mins) the patient started to get a little color back and he stated he was feeling much better.  A second set of vitals was then taken which were  BP: 106/78 the O2 sat 98 and Heart rate was again at 78.  We instructed the patient to please hang around for 30 more minutes and after that time left with the person he was with.
LAB_DATA: only Blood pressure and oxygen sat monitor  as stated above

SYMPTOM_TEXT: weakness; tremors; couldn't tap the phone with her right hand; melted into chair; Shooting pain; numbness; pruritus; fell; had GBS; lymphedama; Acute onset neurological; neuropathy / couldn't raise her head or arms / slumpimg; slurring / couldn't talk; This case was reported by a other health professional via call center representative and described the occurrence of guillain barre syndrome in a female patient who received Flu Seasonal QIV Quebec (FluLaval Quadrivalent 2016-2017 season) for prophylaxis.   On an unknown date, the patient received FluLaval Quadrivalent 2016-2017 season. On 13th January 2020, more than 2 years after receiving FluLaval Quadrivalent 2016-2017 season, the patient experienced neuropathy (serious criteria GSK medically significant). On an unknown date, the patient experienced guillain barre syndrome (serious criteria GSK medically significant), lymphedema, neurological symptom, slurred speech, weakness, tremor, mobility decreased, feeling hot, shooting pain, numbness, pruritus and fall. On an unknown date, the outcome of the guillain barre syndrome, lymphedema, neurological symptom and weakness were not recovered/not resolved and the outcome of the neuropathy, tremor, mobility decreased, feeling hot, shooting pain, numbness, pruritus and fall were unknown and the outcome of the slurred speech was recovered/resolved.   It was unknown if the reporter considered the guillain barre syndrome, neuropathy, lymphedema, neurological symptom, slurred speech, weakness, tremor, mobility decreased, feeling hot, shooting pain, numbness, pruritus and fall to be related to FluLaval Quadrivalent 2016-2017 season.  Additional information was provided as follows: The age at vaccination was not reported. The patient lkely had GBS(guillain barre syndrome) reaction to Flulaval 2016-2017 which was acute and complicated. The patient experienced acute onset neurological and lymphedama 16 hrs post vaccination. It took 5 months for symtoms to resolve. 4th-5th January 2020, the patient experienced acute onset similar symptoms which were ongoing. The patient had a suspect exposure to Covid 19 in December 21, 2019. The symptoms began 13 days later including peripheral neuropathy all 4 limbs, severe lyphedema requiring bilateral carpal tunnel surgeries. The patient had persistent shooting pains, numbness, intense pruritus and other. In mid May 2020, the patient tested for Covid AG and AB, result was negative, unknown which manufacturer made tests. The patient stated that she suspected shouldn't get Flulaval Quad again. The patient wanted to know What was the position on She getting Covid vaccine considering severity of adverse run to Flulaval in 2016. The patient would see immunologist day after reporting 3pm MST. The patient stated that she did not want to be one of those patients who stupidly got another rabies vaccine then went on to develop an autoimmune disease. She at time of reporting hd an autoimmune disease from the flu vaccine. With regard to her experience following Flulaval, she stated she was sitting there and felt like she melted into chair. She couldn't talk. She was slurring.  The patient couldn't raise her head or arms. She fell out of bed. The neuropathy went on for a while. The symptom of slurring pretty well resolved within 48 hours. The weakness still persisted occasionally. She experienced tremors. This time around she did not have tremors but the neuropathy was ridiculous. The patient finally saw a neurologist. She first talked to them in Jan 2017 and finally saw him 2 to 3 weeks before reporting. She did not know. She said it was idiopathic. She had to retire as a result and has had no paycheck since 2019. Her take was that she visited a large aquarium 4 days before Christmas in 2019.  13 to14 days later she experienced virtually that same symptoms as she had 16 hours post flu vaccine, however that time it was much more, maybe another 25 to 30 percent neurologic, the slurring and slumping. The patient couldn't tap the phone with her right hand to call her internist. She had to use her left hand. And tremors persisted. She had to quit doing surgeries. Fast forward symptoms kind of resolved in terms of fine motor things and no tremors. She had to get injections in her thumbs 6x because of the lymphedema. The reporter was not sure if it was due to exposure to the virus (COVID) or vaccine.  The physicians she had been seeing have been contradicting each other. The reporter consented to follow up.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Difficulty breathing; Legs have also itched; Hives painful to touch; Hives; Little nausea; A spontaneous report was received from a consumer, who was a 81-year-old, male, patient, who received Moderna's COVID-19 Vaccine (mRNA-1273) and developed nausea, hives, difficulty breathing, legs have also itched, and hives painful to touch.   The patient's medical history included afib (atrial fibrillation). Products known to have been used by the patient, within two weeks prior to the event, included finasteride, warfarin, sotalol, simvastatin, mesalamine, metoprolol, and oxygen.   On 12 Jan 2021, prior to the onset of the events, the patient received their first of two planned doses of mRNA-1273 intramuscularly in the left arm for prophylaxis of COVID-19 infection.   The patient reported that he felt a little nausea for the first few days after vaccine administration.  On 25 Jan 2021, the patient woke up at 1:00 AM with hives on his right arm from the elbow to the shoulder. He stated the hives were painful to touch. The patient took diphenhydramine and the hives disappeared that morning. Later that day, the patient developed difficulty breathing and the hives appeared on his left arm from the elbow to shoulder.  The patient went to the emergency room and was hospitalized overnight due to breathing issues. He was given diphenhydramine and steroids and was released from the hospital on 26 Jan 2021.    On 27 Jan 2021, the hives reappeared from the patient's hands, spreading to the arms, shoulders, head, neck, and face. He described some of the hives as being nearly a quarter-inch high and he stated they looked like water blisters.  On 28 Jan 2021, the patient went to the emergency room again because he was having a lot of trouble breathing.   On an unknown date, the patient's legs had also itched but there were no spots.   Action taken with mRNA-1273 in response to the events was not provided.   The outcome of the events, nausea, hives, difficulty breathing, legs have also itched, and hives painful to touch, was unknown.; Reporter's Comments: This case concerns an 81 year old, male patient, with medical history of atrial fibrillation, who experienced serious unexpected event of dyspnoea, and non-serious unexpected events of urticaria, pruritus, pain, and non-serious expected event of nausea. The event of nausea occurred on day 1 after mRNA-1273 (Lot# Unknown). The event of dyspnoea, urticaria, and pain occurred 14 days after mRNA-1273 and the event of pruritus occurred on an unspecified date after mRNA-1273. Treatment included diphenhydramine and steroids. Concomitant medications included finasteride, warfarin, sotalol, simvastatin, mesalamine, metoprolol, and oxygen. Very limited information regarding this event has been provided at this time. Based on temporal association between the use of the product and the start date of the events, a causal relationship cannot be excluded. Additional information has been requested.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: really extreme adverse reaction; optical nerve pain; waves coming back of chills; dizziness; diarrhea; outer extremities would just shake; doesn't feel right; don't want to die after having this vaccine; fever; right arm had neurological tingles; elevated heart beat/increased heart rate; felt like really hard pressure on chest; hyperventilating; clammy hands and feet; red rash on cheeks and chest; got really hot; sweating; almost to the point of shortness of breath; lost sensation in face; eyes felt very bulged like a pressure; A spontaneous report was received from a consumer concerning a 34-year-old, female patient, who received Moderna's COVID-19 vaccine (mRNA-1273) and experienced increased heart rate (tachycardia), right arm had neurological tingles (hemiparaesthesia), got really hot (feeling hot), sweating (hyperhidrosis), almost to the point of shortness of breath (dsypnoea), lost sensation in face (sensory loss), eyes felt very bulged like a pressure (ocular discomfort), felt like really hard pressure on chest (chest discomfort), hyperventilating (hyperventilation), clammy hands and feet (cold sweat), and red rash on cheeks and chest (rash erythematous).   The patient's medical history, as provided by the reporter, included anxiety and a history of allergies (but nothing life-threatening).  Concomitant product use was not provided.  On 05 Feb 2021, approximately 15 minutes prior to the onset of symptoms, the patient received their first of two planned doses of mRNA-1273 (Lot number: 013M20A) in the left arm for prophylaxis of COVID-19 infection.  The patient had the first dose of the Moderna vaccine Friday 05 Feb 2021 around 5:00 in left non dominant arm. The patient made the facility aware that she had a history of allergies (but nothing life threatening) so they monitored her for 30 minutes. Within 15 minutes of vaccine administration, the patient developed a red rash on her cheeks and chest. She started getting really, really hot and sweating, and was almost to the point of shortness of breath. The patient got cold water and turned on the air conditioner. She then lost sensation in her face for about an hour and a half, and her eyes felt very "bulged" like a pressure. About 8-12 hours later the occipital bone of her neck was really hot. She feel like she's getting a really extreme adverse reaction. Later Saturday night, 06-Feb-2021, the patient went to the emergency room. She had an elevated heartbeat and increased heart rate, and she felt like really hard pressure was on her chest. The patient was hyperventilating withdeep sweats, and said "it keeps coming on and off". The patient reported still getting clammy hands and clammy feet, and that her heart rate kept going up. Though she got vaccine on the left arm, the patient reported that her right arm had neurological tingles. At the ER, patient was given alprazolam; then she was asked to leave. Patient stated she was having waves where she had elevated heart rate about 140-160 and high intense heat along with optical nerve pain.  Patient took diphenhydramine which she stated slowed down the heart rate and provided relief although patient was still experiencing waves coming back of chills, fever, sweating and elevated heart rate.  On morning of 10 Feb 2021, the patient woke from sleep with extreme high heart rate and she broke out in a sweat.  The patient experienced dizziness, diarrhea, and her occipital area behind the neck got extremely hot.  She also reported that the rash came back on her chest, and her legs and outer extremities would shake. The patient stated "it doesn't feel right. I don't want to die after having this vaccine. The warm fuzzy reaction has just not gone from my body."  Action taken with mRNA-1273 in response to the events was unknown.  The outcomes of the events, increased heart rate, right arm had neurological tingles, got really hot, sweating, almost to the point of shortness of breath, lost sensation in face, eyes felt very bulged like a pressure, felt like really hard pressure on chest, hyperventilating, clammy hands and feet, and red rash on cheeks and chest were not reported.; Reporter's Comments: Very limited information regarding this events has been provided at this time.  Further information has been requested.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: chronic small vessel ischemic disease; Felt Bad; Arm pain; Headache; Body ache; Sweating; Cold Feet; Tremors; Slurred speech; Elevated blood pressure; Stuttering; A spontaneous report was received from a Healthcare professional concerning a 31 Years-old female patient who received Moderna's COVID-19 vaccine (mRNA-1273) and experienced non-serious events of body pain, headache, arm pain, hyperhidrosis, peripheral coldness, tremor, dysarthria, elevated blood pressure, dysphonia and serious event of exacerbation of preexisting chronic small vessel ischemic disease after the 2nd dose of Moderna vaccine chronic .  The patient's medical history was not provided. No relevant concomitant medications were reported.  On 21-JAN-2021, prior to the onset of the events, the patient received their second dose of planned doses of mRNA-1273 batch no:028L20A  intramuscularly in the Anatomical location for prophylaxis of COVID-19 infection.  On the same day, The patient experienced arm pain, headache, sweating, body ache, cold feet, tremors, slurred speech, elevated blood pressure measured at 183/90., and sluttering.  On 21-JAN-2021, CT brain normal. MRI was abnormal and showed flare signal regions in the brain which signified early microvascular ischemic changes, a demyelinating process, vasculitis, or sequelae for migraines. The subject was treated with intravenously with lorazepam 2mg and Benadryl.  On 03-FEB-2021, the subject was referred to a neurologist and was improving.  On 05-FEB-2021, another MRI was performed and showed multiple scattered punctate foci of unenhancing white matter, signal alteration which were nonspecific but unchanged in comparison to previous MRI. Report suggested that findings were most likely to reflect an early onset chronic small vessel ischemic disease, other somewhat less likely considerations in a patient of this age would include migraine syndrome, various cerebral vasculopathies, or demyelinating conditions.  Action taken with mRNA-1273 in response to the events was not applicable as second dose had been administered.   The outcome of the event was resolving.; Reporter's Comments: The non-serious events of pain, headache, sweating, body ache, cold feet, tremors, slurred speech, elevated blood pressure, and sluttering are temporarily associated with the mRNA-1273 use and a causal association cannot be excluded.  The serious event of chronic small vessel ischemic disease is considered a pre-existing event based a diagnostic findings and thus assessed as unlikely associated with mRNA-1273 use.

An 85-year-old female patient received her 1st dose of BNT162B2 (PFIZER-BIONTECH COVID-19 VACCINE, lot number: EL8982) at single dose via an unknown route injection in left arm on 23Jan2021 around 08:15 for Covid-19 immunization. Medical history included ongoing blood pressure high which was controlled with medication, allergic to penicillin and acetylsalicylic acid;ascorbic acid (ASPIRIN).  She had lost weight and shrunk according to when she went to the doctor 2 months ago. No other products were taken. No history of all previous immunization with the Pfizer vaccine considered as suspect; no vaccines administered on same date with the Pfizer vaccine considered as suspect. No other vaccinations within four weeks prior to the first administration date of the suspect vaccine, no events following prior vaccinations. No family medical history relevant to the events. Patient passed out on her way home on 23Jan2021 (unknown time). The event required a visit to Emergency room, but not a Physician office. The event clinical course was as follows: She got the first dose of the Covid-19 vaccine on Saturday 23Jan2021. Patient reported that after being monitored at the vaccination site for 20minutes, she left to go catch the bus and fainted before boarding the bus.  She remembered getting on the bus, but did not remember crossing the street. She passed out and was unconscious. An ambulance was called and they took her back to the hospital where she got the vaccine. She was taken by ambulance back to the ER, stayed for half the day, she received IV fluids, and a brain scan due to her fall. She stated that she still feels kind of weak as of 29Jan2021.  She did not know what time it happened, because she lost her sense of time on that day because she did not remember. When she got to the hospital she woke up and wondered where she was because she did not remember what happened. They got an x-ray of her head to see if she had bumped it, but it was negative. She did have a bruise on both knees. They gave her IV fluids, and kept her there for a little while, then sent her home. She called her doctor the next day, but he was busy, so she talked to the nurse. No treatment was recommended, just said to get a lot of rest. She was scheduled for the 2nd dose on 13Feb2021 and was scared to death. Patient verified that she was not admitted to the hospital. Investigation assessment were performed. They hooked her up to the monitor, did an x-ray and a CT scan while at the hospital on 23Jan2021 which were normal (both fine), and gave her IV fluids. Outcome of fainted, fall, passed out and was unconscious was resolved on 23Jan2021. Outcome of kind of feel weak was not resolved. Outcome of the other event was unknown.; Sender's Comments: Considering the temporal association, a causal association between administration of BNT162B2 and the onset of fainted and unconscious cannot be fully excluded.  The underlying history of high blood pressure for this 85 years old patient  might provide an alternative explanation. On 17 Feb 2021, prior to the onset of the symptom, the patient received their first of two planned doses of mRNA-1273 (Batch Number: 011J20A) intramuscularly for prophylaxis of COVID-19 infection. On 19 Feb 2021, approximately 2 hours prior to the onset of symptoms, the patient received second of two planned doses of mRNA-1273 (Batch Number: 41L20A) intramuscularly in the left arm for prophylaxis of COVID-19 infection.  On 17 Feb 2021, the patient experienced muscle pain. On 19 Feb 2021, after two hours of vaccination, the patient experienced intense itching 2-4" across on injection site. Eight hours post second shot patient's injection site was very red (Golf Ball Size), hard to the touch and swollen. 25 hours after the injection patient developed mild chills followed by blackout and had to go bed, intense itching and redness from shoulder to elbow.   Treatment for the event included Hydrocortisone cream.  Action taken with mRNA-1273 in response to the events was not provided.  The outcome of the events mild chills, started blackout, intense itching and was reported recovering. The outcome of the events itching across on injection site, injection site was very red (golf ball size), hard to the touch and swollen injection site was reported recovered. The outcome of the events muscle pain, itching and redness from shoulder to elbow was not reported.; Reporter's Comments: Based on the information provided which includes a strong temporal association, and the known safety profile of the  mRNA-1273  vaccine, a causal association between the reported events and the administration of vaccine cannot be excluded.
HISTORY: Medical History/Concurrent Conditions: No adverse event (No medical history provided.)

Janssen COVID-19 Vaccine EUA I received my dose at 3pm on March 12, and experienced no adverse events until about 5 or 6 hours later. Between 8pm and 9pm, I felt a bit tired, though wasn?t sure it was vaccine-related at first. However, I shortly afterwards started feeling much more tired, and experienced chills and shivering. I went to sleep. My wife later said I felt very warm, though we did not measure my temperature.  During the night, at one point, I got up to go to the bathroom, and became very dizzy and nearly fell over, though I was able to catch myself and did not experience any fall or injury.   I went back to bed. At some other point during the night, I started sweating. My wife later said I felt cold at that point.  For most of the following day, Saturday, March 13, I no longer felt dizzy nor overly hot or cold, but had a migraine and mild nausea. I did not vomit, but I also ate very little during the day. I did eat a little in the morning, and had some water throughout the day. For the most part, I laid in bed, drifting in and out of sleep.   At about 7pm on March 13, I took two Tylenol to try to fight the headache. By 8pm I felt almost completely better. I ate more bits of food, and have felt fine since then. Sunday, I woke up and felt back to normal. I ate normally as well.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: About 5 to 10 minutes after the shot I felt extremely lightheaded and then fainted.  When I came to about 10 seconds later, there was a public health official there rubbing my chest asking me if I knew where I was.  It took me a second to fully come to my senses but then I realized where I was and what had happened.  I was very pale, felt chills, was sweating, and it took effort to open my hands.  The EMTs ran a bunch of tests, my Blood pressure was low (I think the number I remember was 104/33), but the rest of the measurements like blood sugar or the number of ekg like tests they did all came back normal.  The EMTs in the field said they think it was a response to the vaccine.  After about 20 minutes of the EMTs monitoring me, my numbers came back up and I was feeling relatively normal.  I waited another 30 minutes before leaving just to make sure.  It has been almost a week and I haven't felt any symptoms close to that since then.

She had the injection, had the usual side effects, did not have fever, nothing out of the ordinary.  Then on Sunday 2/28/21 at approximately 8:00 AM she started having pressure in her chest, radiating to her left shoulder, left neck, left arm and across the shoulder blades.    She  never had any heart issues or blood pressure issues.    Went to the ER and her cardiac enzymes were elevated, and her EKG's indicated she was having a heart attack.  She was lift flighted to the next major hospital and had a cardiac Cath which found a 25% blockage in one spot.  They are stating that they do not know what caused this.  When she informed them that she had the vaccine they told her to report this information.   Her BP was high in the hospital and did not come down much during the hospital stay.  She was put on Cardizem, and Crestor, as well as started on 81mg aspirin.   She is now under the care of a cardiologist, but has recovered from the initial reactions.
LAB_DATA: Blood work showed elevated cardiac enzymes.  EKG's suggested a heart attack.  Cardiac cath showed 25% blockage, but nothing major.    Echocardiogram that was insignificant, nothing to show anything of concern.

Problem with injection, not vaccine.  Tech used VERY LARGE and hollow needle.  She had trouble plunging it into  my (left) arm and I could feel it slicing through tissue.  I gasped as the pain was so extreme and it was all I could do to not cry.  Upon withdrawal, she was shocked that I was bleeding -- drops flowing out of injection site down to my elbow.  She had to ask another tech to help her stop the flow and wipe up the blood drips. That night, throbbing pain in my arm kept me from sleeping and I could not raise my arm without pain  for almost a month.   By the next day, I had a large hematoma.  Injection site continued to bleed internally over the next month.   Developed extensive bruising that kept "refreshing" as injection site continued to bleed internally (pooled red blood that would fade to green only to have more red appear).  Bruising spread to approx. 2.5" wide and 3.5" high.  It has been 4.5 weeks and it is still bruised and tender.  Received dose 2 on 3/14 with no issues or pain whatsoever.  I thought dose 1 injection used a defective needle but medical professional I have spoken to think the tech used a blunt fill needle by mistake.  I was shown a series of needles/sizes and identified the blunt fill one.  I will never forget it!  I was advised to get a COVID antibody test 2 weeks after dose 2 as no one can be sure the vaccine didn't wash out with all the blood.
LAB_DATA: Will  have a COVID antibody test on March 29 (2 weeks after dose #2).

Patient had history of fainting noted on  patient also notified immunizer of history.  Vaccine was administered and patient appeared to be ok.  She was told to have a seat and wait 30 minutes to ensure patient safety.  Immunizer notified me/pharmacist of patient's history and staff was informed to watch her for any adverse events.  5-10 minutes later patient walked up to counsel window and notified pharmacist she was going to faint.  I asked her to please return to her seat and immediately a technician and I went out and assisted her to a chair.  We provided a bottle of water and advised her to sip some.  After a few more minutes she passed out in the chair.  At that point we called 911.  The operator advised us to lay her flat.  We moved her into the training room and waited for EMT to arrive.  They arrived a few minutes later.  At that point she was beginning to come around.  I left to return to pharmacy as she was being cared for.  20 minutes later the EMT consulted me and patient vitals were good and she was feeling much better and refused to be transported to hospital.  I signed off their form as a witness of her refusal.

About 12 hours exactly after getting the 2nd dose I got extreme POTS flare up and a mild occular migraine.  I had a fever that kept going from the mid 99s to the 101s for 36 hrs.  Was freezing and burning and had lots of joint and body pain.  Most people I know had all of that, but the reason I?m reporting is the tachycardia.  My tachy has been fairly well controlled with meds and after my second dose it was so bad any time I sat up, I couldn?t breath, my tachy got so bad, my heart rate would jump from up to 70bpms, just sitting up.  My resting heart rate on meds has been 60-80, and for those 36 hours was 80-110.  Anytime I did anything my heart rate would jump to 130-150 and I could NOT BREATH.  My SpO2 was fine, so I know that the issue was my POTS flaring up and that it was the tachy.  I just want to report that it could cause issues with people with dysautonomia, so they don?t freak out if it happens.  My heart rate is still elevated, but is slowly going back down.

I got the vaccine last Thursday, March 4, 2021 and I am experiencing strange side effects. I wanted to be sure to send this along to you as well as, to the adverse effect website. It?s almost as if I?ve had a stroke. Initially (after the shot), I was a little lightheaded but as the rest of the day wore on, (say around 6 hours later), I started to get foggy in my brain - like I had to remember to even breathe - and tightness in my chest like asthma. There was a high pitch scream in my ears and I was more or less, kind of out of it. My hands and feet were sweating profusely. My tongue kind of reacted, too and got a little burned, like when I eat pineapple. It was then that I noticed difficulty swallowing. My sister (a medical professional) suggested Benadryl for the mouth and tongue sensation and she kept an eye on me the rest of the night. She also warned that I should not get a second shot (I totally agree). Being a trooper, I thought all of the weird stuff would blow over in a day or two, so I decided to power on and not report my issues.  Today is day 6 post vaccine and I can now see a pattern to the symptoms or episodes which are still present, on and off:  1. The ringing in my ears will intensify, and then I stare off into space, my words get garbled (I have to really concentrate on being present), my tongue gets very dry and then the swallowing issue returns (it?s like slow motion swallowing, so I bite my tongue to stay in the moment).  2. The tightness in my chest intensifies and my breathing gets shallow. I must focus and breath through it despite discomfort. Note, since the shot, I keep a Benydryl and my inhaler with me, although I haven?t used Benadryl since day 3. I used my inhaler yesterday, day 5 because of discomfort and that seemed to help, but using it triggered an ear ringing/screaming episode that came and went the rest of the day.  3. I also have nasal constriction throughout the day. The nasal passage just inflames and then relaxes. I also have phantom smells and my sense of taste got a little off on day 1, but recovered. ________________  March 18, 2021 Update  Saturday, 3/13 went to the ER because the cognitive issues had advanced. I found myself staring off into space, losing my train of thought, and unable to speak. When I did speak I stammered or stuttered. They wanted to make sure I did not have a stroke or that I was not in the middle of one, so they did some tests. They also recommended that I go ahead and take the prednisone.  After my ER visit the cognitive issues continued, but began to be not-so-frequent by Sunday afternoon. I felt like I was on the road to recovery and so delayed again, taking the prednisone.  On Tuesday (3/16), I had what I would call an asthma attack. I was having very strong bronchial spasms that would not abate. I used my rescue inhaler to try to mitigate the symptoms, but that did not work. At the same time, the cognitive issues sort of returned and the big loud ringing and whooshing  in my ears was really really noticeable.  I am having a protracted allergic reaction to the vaccine. I am not normally allergic to things, but I have noticed new allergies since this all began. Certain food items seem to bother me now and push me into the lung seizing, raw tongue, neurological, ear ringing event.
ALLERGIES: Pineapple hurts my tongue and so do walnuts

She pre-medicated with famotidine 40mg, prednisone 30mg, and cetirizine 20mg last night and this morning, per plan from her allergist. In ED, Given 60 mg solumedrol and 25 mg IV benadryl. Follow up evaluation with minimal improvement in symptoms at 1300. Subsequent evaluation at 1415 with new diffuse itchiness throughout body, similar throat tightness, with report of mildly more labored breathing. On re-evaluation, patient with persistent pruritus however no new or worsening throat swelling, difficulty breathing, shortness of breath.  Patient did not have abdominal pain, nausea or vomiting.  Patient given additional dose of Benadryl, discharged home with clear return precautions.  Patient has EpiPen at home, will continue to take prednisone as an outpatient  Of note, after patient received first dose of COVID vaccine on 2/17/21, patient developed similar throat tightness and perioral numbness

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Within 15-minutes of vaccination, the patient had a syncopal event preceded by nausea and lightheadedness. EMS evaluated the patient on-site. The patient was pale, diaphoretic, and hypotensive (67/37).  EKG (3/12): Sinus brady, rate 46 bpm, no ST elevation. FSBG (3/12): 89mg/dl. EMS administered 500mL IV saline. EMS transported the patient to Hospital Emergency Department. In the ED, the patient feels back at baseline and was normotensive (119/72). Patient stated they have a history of vasovagal response and vasovagal vomiting, but had never experienced a vasovagal syncope episode. Physician administered 0.5mg Lorazepam. The ED physician admitted the patient to the telemetry unit for vasovagal syncope due to patient's prodrome and prior history of similar near syncopal episodes. Inpatient attending agreed that the patient's vasovagal response may be secondary to poor PO intake with extreme stress. Patient's admission was less than 1-day and stated they were anxious to return home. Discharged with diagnoses of Mild leukocytosis, Vasovagal response, and Orthostatic hypotension secondary to dehydration.
LAB_DATA: CBC/CMP (3/12): WBC 14.5 - Leukocytosis  UA (3/12): Unremarkable  Troponin (3/12): 0.00  HCG Qual (3/12): Negative  EKG (3/12): NSR, no signs of acute ischemia or infarct, no prolonged QTC, Brugada sign, delta wave, hyper inverted deep T waves. CXR (3/12): No acute cardiopulmonary findings.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Four days after, I noticed a soft "lump" right axilla. Cancer Institute did an ultrasound.  "No enlarged lymph nodes." No sign of cancer The lump in my axilla got very large. "Not as big as a baseball but larger than a golf ball." I could wrap my fingers around it. Hard as a rock. Within a week my whole entire chest wall on the right (from side to sternum) was scarlet red. And I was getting another "lump" in the fold of tissue where my upper chest meets my upper arm.  I was put on Keflex 500 mg four times a day.   The redness in my chest wall subsided. Five days after being on Keflex, the lump on my chest was hard, red, very painful, "angry." Fevers, feeling "pretty sick." (Very uncharacteristic of me. I didn't miss a day of work through months of multiple rounds of chemo, 5 weeks of radiation.)   February 7 PCP requested I go the ER. Suspecting an abscess. They did an I&D. Expressed "lots of puss" and left a drain in. To be removed in 5 days. Placed on Bactrim twice a day for 5 days.
HISTORY: 5 years post right mastectomy. 13 lymph nodes removed. Chemo. 5 weeks radiation. (To me: the laying down of radiated tissue/ scar tissue.)

Within 15-minutes of vaccination, the patient reported dizziness and a headache after receiving the second dose of the Pfizer vaccine. EMS evaluated the patient on-site. The patient was hypertensive (150/88) with an FSBG of 188mg/dl. EKG demonstrated pacer rhythm, no ectopy. The patient refused EMS transport. The patient then proceeded to Hospital Emergency Department. In the ED, the patient reported feeling lightheaded, a headache, and nausea without vomiting. During the ED visit, the patient reported mild improvement, but stated that she noticed some lightheadedness when standing. The physician administered 1L IV saline bolus, 4mg Zofran IV, and 1G of Acetaminophen PO. Tests were relatively unremarkable. The patient had improved and was discharged with diagnoses of Medication reaction (Pfizer COVID vaccine), HA, Dizziness, and Orthostasis without hypotension.

I had a minor reaction on day 2-3 post-vaccine administration; minor arm pain, perhaps some fatigue. I took ibuprofen once at bedtime on day 2. No further discomfort . On day 8 post-vaccination, I woke up with the sensation that my arm was sore at the vaccine site. The same morning, looked at my arm and found it to be quite red in a 3-4 inch diameter irregular blotch surrounding the vaccine site. It was a bit redder at the edges, but fairly uniformly hot pink throughout. It itched a good bit. Some internet sleuthing (sorry!) revealed that the appearance and timing are consistent with what's being called 'covid arm'.  I took two doses of ibuprofen that day. The discomfort  was manageable and did not get worse. These symptoms subsided gradually and 7 days after onset, it appears completely resolved.
OTHER_MEDS: Claritin, Allegra, Azelastine spray (all for seasonal allergies at the typical dosages). Fish oil, calcium, vitamin D, and iron (for cholesterol, vitamin D deficiency, and mild periodic anemia during perimenopause).
CUR_ILL: None. I have been sequestered since March 2020 other than critical needs, and I have managed to avoid all illness as far as I know.
HISTORY: Nothing not already mentioned. I appear to be in pretty good health in middle age.
ALLERGIES: No medications or other products. I have a serious allergy to all molluscs that were tested by an allergist in 2019 (I rated a '4' on the cutaneous scratch test and the injection follow up was never carried out because my initial response was so severe).

About midnight, I woke up feeling really bad chills and I checked my temperature and I had fever of 101. I took Tylenol. No amount of blankets could make me feel like I wasn't freezing. After a few hours, I went back to sleep and had off and on fever and chills and whole body aches - especially stomach - for next four days. I rotated Tylenol and Motrin every 4-6 days. After fourth day, stomach pain got worse where it hurt to breathe. The chills had gone away. I thought I had constipation because  of the pain meds and I tried to take a laxative but that didn't help it all and it made the pain worse.  I went to URGENT CARE January 18- gave me Flagel and Cipro  and they ordered Ultrasound which I had on the 19th. - Covid test - negative. Put me on Vancomycin - after the Flagel - I took that for 10 days. That helped with symptoms.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Woke on the morning after the shot 2/27/21 with a low grade fever (100), fatigue, headache, joint and muscle pain and slightly swollen lymph nodes in my neck.  Within a few hours, my body was completely covered in large hives from head to toe.  I rested or slept most of the day and by the afternoon, the fever had subsided.  By the next day headache, joint/muscle pain and swollen lymph nodes diminished.  I still felt fatigue and the hives were awful.   Began taking Benadryl with no relief.  Called my primary care doctor to report; increased Benadryl dosage to 2 every 4 hours.  There was some relief during the day, but the large doses of benadryl were making me anxious/nervous, racing heart, shakes.   Decreased following another call to Doctor and began taking Antronex; decreaed side effects, but little affect on the hives during the evening/overnight hours.  At times I would be completely covered in them, other times they were localized (bottoms of my feet, face, neck, eyes).   Returned call to Doctor, again suggested Prednisone. (I typically have strong reactions to steriods and wanted to avoid if at all possible) Began first dose 3/18/2021.  Experiencing some relief already.
OTHER_MEDS: Prescriptions: Levothyroxine Suppliments:  Cataplex C, Vitamin D/K2, Zinc, Magnesium, Clariton D
ALLERGIES: No medication or food allergies.  I do have medication and food sensitivities and thus try to avoid these things.  Seasonal allergies; esp. spring and fall (grass, molds, pollens) typically controlled with Clariton D or Zyrtec D and Flonase during peak times.

No signs of anaphalaxis.  Will need further monitoring.   ED Note: This is a well-appearing and pleasant 30-year-old female who presented to the emergency department for generalized body itching following getting the first dose of Pfizer COVID-19 vaccine at approximately 930 this morning.  On presentation patient is well-appearing, respirations are even and nonlabored, she is speaking in complete sentences with normal work of breathing.  She denies any symptoms other than itching currently on her upper arms and upper back.  She notes that the itching is already starting to resolve and has lessened.  There is no rash present on exam, no hives.  Airway is clear, uvula midline, patient is tolerating secretions well with no drooling or voice changes and there is no mouth or tongue swelling present.  Neck is supple without lymphadenopathy.  Patient was observed close to an hour and a half and she remained stable with no changes.  At time of discharge patient with no skin reaction, facial, mouth, or tongue swelling.  She is speaking in complete sentences with normal work of breathing, respirations even and nonlabored.  She appears well and appropriate for discharge.  I had an in-depth discussion with her regarding monitoring her symptoms at home seeking emergent care if she has any compromise. We discussed all signs and symptoms that she should look for that would be concerning and need emergent intervention. She indicated that she understood all instructions. Patient was given the opportunity to ask questions.  All questions and concerns were thoroughly addressed.  Patient indicated she understood all instructions was comfortable with this plan of care. No evidence of Stevens-Johnson syndrome, anaphylaxis, cellulitis, or systemic compromise. Feel supportive care and symptomatic treatment reasonable. I reviewed recent and relevant Chart Entries, Previous Notes, Previous Labs, Previous Radiology studies. Patient ambulated out of the emergency department with a steady gait.  Received benadryl and famotidine in the ED and take home prescriptions for famotidine and hydroxyzine.

33 y.o. female with history of asthma, SVT, sickle cell trait, eosinophilic esophagitis, asthma, preeclampsia presenting to ER today with scratchy throat after Covid vaccine.  Patient was observed for a total of 45 minutes, and brought to the emergency room for provider evaluation.  She denies difficulty breathing, difficulty swallowing, throat swelling, drooling or pain.  She denies URI complaints, fevers, chills, lightheadedness, dizziness, nausea or vomiting.   ED Update: She was given famotidine and Benadryl here in the emergency room.  She has no demonstration of hives, rash, induration, or swelling at the injection site.  Differential diagnoses for this patient include allergic reaction, however this is most likely related to anxiety.   Patient had improvement after medications, was able tolerate p.o. without difficulty.  She is no longer complaining of scratchiness in her throat.  She states she has Benadryl at home, recommended she can also take Zyrtec daily.  Discussed worsening symptoms and when to seek immediate care in the emergency room.  Patient verbalized understanding of teaching, feel that she is stable for discharge as she is able to verbalize red flag symptoms.  She is able to ambulate out of ER with steady gait.

Note from ED: This is a well-appearing and pleasant 72-year-old female who presented via ambulance for itching response after receiving the Pfizer COVID-19 vaccine today. Patient is very well-appearing. Skin is normal and well-appearing there is no rash or erythema. Patient is speaking in complete sentences with normal work of breathing. Respirations are even and nonlabored. Lung fields are clear to auscultation bilaterally throughout patient denies any shortness of breath or breathing issues, cough or itchy throat. Airway is clear with no tongue or mouth swelling, floor mouth is soft and not elevated mandible is easily palpated, throat is nontender, neck is supple. Heart rate is within normal limits with regular rhythm. She was provided with Benadryl and famotidine as treatment for her itching. Patient was observed for greater than 2-1/2 hours in the emergency department. Patient noted that itching markedly reduced with use of Benadryl I felt patient was appropriate and stable for discharge. I had an in-depth discussion with her regarding she monitor her symptoms closely at home we discussed all symptoms that she should look for that would be concerning and she should make sure to seek emergent care. She was given the opportunity ask questions. All question concerns were thoroughly addressed. Patient indicated she felt good with her care here today with discharge and would monitor herself at home. She was picked up by her husband would also be home to monitor her. Advised her to follow-up with her primary care provider regarding recommendations for whether she should receive her second dose of the vaccine. Provided her with CDC printed out recommendations for vaccine allergic reaction. She was given the opportunity ask questions. All questions and concerns were addressed and answered to the best of my ability. No evidence of Stevens-Johnson syndrome, anaphylaxis, cellulitis, or systemic compromise Feel supportive care and symptomatic treatment reasonable. Urged dermatologic follow up. At time of discharge patient remained well-appearing not in any type of acute distress. She ambulated out of the emergency department with a steady gait. I reviewed recent and relevant Chart Entries, Previous Notes, Previous Labs, Previous Radiology studies.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient presented to the ED on 3/14 11:30PM with difficulty swallowing.  Patient received Pfizer vaccine on 3/13 at 4:30pm.  Immediately afterward she had sensation of lip and tongue swelling.  She was given Zyrtec and monitored by the vaccination clinic for 30 minutes.  She was discharged from the clinic after improvement of systems.  Lip swelling presented on 3/14 at 2:00pm and she took Zyrtec.  At 10pm, patient felt sensation of swelling in throat and presented to ED.  EMS gave patient 50 mg IV Benadryl.   Patient discharged on prednisone.  Patient re-presented to ED on 3/16.  Allergic symptoms subsided, but patient complained of atypical chest pain with paliptations, tremulousness.  Suspect adverse reaction prednisone.  She was given cardiology referral for follow up if her symptoms persisted.  She remained in normal sinus rhythm with initial sinus tachycardia.  Was discharged home in stable condition and counseled to return to ED for any concerns.
LAB_DATA: On physical exam on 3/14 in ED, there were no signs of oropharyngeal or respiratory compromise.  Vital signs are normal with no hypoxia.  Lungs are clear to auscultation without any wheezing.  No stridor.  Because patient had sensation of swelling, patient was given IV fluids, IV Solu-Medrol, and IV Pepcid, and an additional 50 mg IV Benadryl.  Patient was educated that steroids may blunt the immune response but patient understood risk and wanted steroids.  Patient placed on continuous cardiac monitoring and pulse ox.  Was given prescription for prednisone.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient is a 3-month-old male who was admitted from the infectious disease clinic today for further workup of fever and rash.     Patient was seen today in clinic along with both of his parents. History, per chart review:   Symptoms began on Jan. 5th: Vomited forcefully for first time - very forceful. Did not happen again. On the 7th, got first set of immunizations including Rotavirus. Slight fever afterwards x 24 hours. On the 10th/11th, noted to have blood in stool multiple times, resolved within two days of Mom starting dairy free diet.    On the 15th had increased fussiness with fever 101.9 rectal temperature. Mom unbundled him and temperature decreased that night to 100.6. This fever persisted, so they presented to the ER the morning of the 16th. Had Covid nasal PCR (negative), RVAP (negative), normal UA, CXR - normal and work up negative (no LP performed).  Given TYLENOL and d/c'd home. Right before going home, mom noticed a lesion on foot that looked like a "halo". By the time they got home, rash/lesions spread over both feet. Patient continued to have fever 100.6-100.8.     Went back to the ER on the 17th and had T-103 rectally. Rash was worse and spread to palm of right hand and hand reportedly turned blue. Testicles also appeared red and "tight", particularly the left testicle. In ER, eyes began to look "blood shot" and developed more diarrhea. Given TYLENOL had repeat CBC and blood cx.  Was admitted to hospital for observation at that time. US of testicles done, and flow was normal. At this point, eyes were "completely red", and rash appeared on hands. On the 18th, blood in stool re-appeared and fever continued (still in hospital). Labs reportedly all normal except for elevated AST/ALT and thrombocytosis - parents told that this looked like "inflammation".   Evening of the 18th received one dose of Ceftriaxone. Fever decreased but blood in stool continued. Discharged to home at this time. Afebrile x 36 hours, but then fever returned to 100.6 on the 20th and breaking through TYLENOL. Rash started to develop on face/ear at this time. Yesterday (the 21st), fever increased to 101.3 and rash seemed worse. Referred to clinic at this time.   This morning, T- 100.6, given TYLENOL prior to being seen today. Parents state that rash is still progression. Last blood in stool was on the 19th.   No LP or echocardiogram performed during this time period of illness.    No vomiting since this 5th. No obvious swelling of joints but parents state feet were swollen on the 17th/18th. Conjunctival injection now gone.  No lethargy or excessive irritability and continues to smile/interact with parents.    Birth Hx/Fam hx - Mom was COVID tested at 39 and 40 weeks of pregnancy, both negative, but not tested since. Mom breast feeding. Breast feeding schedule good as per mom - usually 1-2 hours during the day and often much longer overnight (has even slept up to 7-8 hours once). Feeds well, growing and developing normally as per parents. Dad healthy, no medications or medical conditions. Dad had COVID test 2 months ago and negative.    Lives at home with both parents, new home (2015).  3 dogs and 2 parakeets at home. Bird cages in different parts of the house. Dogs do not come into nursery, but patient is in contact with dogs. No tick bites noted or ticks on baby. Dogs all treated for ticks. Grandparents have not visited and no visitors in home since he has been born. Father (lawyer) and Mom (accountant) both telecommute for work at this time.    No other complaints.   Last dose of TYLENOL was given for fever, at 5 30 pm.   SUMMARY OF HOSPITAL COURSE:   Admitted to general pediatrics due to concern for atypical Kawasaki Disease. Peds consulted at admission. An echo was obtained and resulted negative for coronary artery aneurysm or ectasia. Also obtained a skull XR to evaluate the lesion on his head which was negative for osseous abnormality. On 1/23, he received IVIG with significant improvement in rash. He was pretreated with TYLENOL and BENADRYL and was also started on high dose aspirin. Blood cultures obtained prior to IVIG resulted no growth. He remained afebrile after receiving IVIG for 48 hours. On the day of discharge, he has been eating well with adequate UOP. He was transitioned to low dose aspirin (5 mg/kg/day), which he should continue for at least 6 weeks, or as determined by Pediatric Cardiology (f/u scheduled for 2/11).  Family was counseled that if Pt develops another fever in the next week, parents should call his PCP or return to ER as he may require additional treatment for atypical KD. Parents were also counseled that Pt should not receive MMR or varicella vaccines for 11 months following IVIG treatment.   Interval History: Mom states that Pt did well overnight. He breast feed almost every hour with no concerns. His energy level is back to normal and his UOP was adequate.   PHYSICAL EXAMINATION AT DISCHARGE:   Discharge Weight:  Wt Readings from Last 1 Encounters:  01/22/21 5.715 kg (12 lb 9.6 oz) (17 %, Z= -0.97) *   * Growth percentiles are based on WHO (Boys, 0-2 years) data.   Visit Vitals BP 89/47 (BP Location: Right leg, Patient Position: Supine)  Pulse 137  Temp 36.8 �C (98.2 �F) (Axillary)  Resp 34  Ht 0.615 m (2' 0.21")  SpO2 100%  BMI 15.11 kg/m�   Temp: [36.2 �C (97.1 �F)-36.9 �C (98.4 �F)]  Heart Rate: [118-156]  Resp: [30-44]  BP: (78-114)/(41-59)  SpO2: [98 %-100 %]   I/O (Last 24 hours) at 1/25/2021 1217 Last data filed at 1/25/2021 0938 Intake?  Output 450 ml  Net -450 ml   UOP: 1.49 ml/kg/hr Mixed: 433 ml  Physical Exam Constitutional: Well, developed, well nourished. No distress  HENT: Anterior fontanelle is flat. Nose normal. No nasal discharge.  Mouth/Throat: Mucous membranes are moist. Oropharynx is clear. No oral or nasal lesions  Eyes: Conjunctivae normal, no injection or discharge  Neck: Normal range of motion. Neck supple. No LAD.  Cardiovascular: Normal rate, regular rhythm. Pulses are palpable. No murmur heard. Pulmonary/Chest: Effort normal and breath sounds normal. No respiratory distress.  Abdominal: Soft. Bowel sounds are normal. He exhibits no distension and no mass. There is no hepatosplenomegaly. There is no abdominal tenderness.  Musculoskeletal: Normal range of motion. No tenderness, deformity, signs of injury or edema. No notable joint edema or erythema  Lymphadenopathy: No occipital adenopathy is present. He has no cervical adenopathy.  Neurological: He is alert. He has normal strength. He exhibits normal muscle tone. Suck normal. Strong grasp. Extremities: Orange brown chromonychia on multiple nails improving Skin: Skin is warm and dry. Capillary refill takes less than 3 seconds. Turgor is normal. No petechiae and no purpura noted. He is not diaphoretic. No cyanosis. No mottling, jaundice or pallor. Non-blanching macules/papules that were present at admission have greatly improved. Now mostly present on feet with one spot.    DISCHARGE DISPOSITION: Home with family   FOLLOW-UP APPOINTMENTS/ARRANGEMENTS:  Future Appointments  Date Time  2/11/2021 10:00 AM   Family to schedule follow up as needed with PCP  Patient should not receive MMR or varicella vaccine for 11 months after receiving IVIG.   From Cardiologist: ASSESSMENT/PLAN  Pt is an otherwise healthy 3-month-old male with a recent history of Kawasaki disease, successfully treated with one dose of IVIG. He did not have coronary artery involvement apparent on his acute phase echocardiogram and continues to have normal appearing coronary arteries. The CV sequelae of Kawasaki disease are coronary artery aneurysms, most commonly detected in the acute phase or within 4 weeks of the illness. He has been on low dose aspirin to prevent thrombosis within any coronary artery aneurysms or ectasia that may have developed. He is approximately 4 weeks post the onset of illness and there is no evidence of coronary artery disease today so I will plan to stop his aspirin. Given his young age, I will plan to follow him up again in 1 year to reevaluate for evidence of coronary artery disease. His mother will call if he experiences difficulty feeding, unexplained irritability, or prolonged sustained tachypnea.  Pt also has a patent foramen ovale, which is a part of persistent fetal circulation. This communication is likely to close on its own without significant hemodynamic issues, but we will reassess with echo when he returns for follow up. No interventions or further testing are required in the interim.   Our recommendations are as follows:   Cardiac Medications: may d/c aspirin Activity Restrictions: None SBE Prophylaxis: Not indicated Vaccinations: As recommended by PCP including seasonal flu vaccine. Synagis is not indicated for cardiovascular reasons.  Follow-up: in 1 year  Pediatric Cardiology

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I was surprised about the handling of the vaccine and wanted to report the way it was handled in case this has an effect on the potential efficacy for people who came in that day. I checked the CDC guidelines which seemed to not have been followed.  Instead of preparing the syringes right before the vaccination and administering them then, the vaccine was given with prepared syringes which were prefilled and some earlier time. I witnessed at least 10 prefilled syringes and one vial sitting mixed loosely in a household plastic basket next to a station. The syringes from that basket were used to vaccinate people one after another.    Furthermore, they were stored in said basket in direct sun on a warm window sill for the entire time I was able to observe this (~15 minutes). At one point the technician who used the syringes from the basket was told by another staffer to not prefill and let sit around that many syringes but did not act on it.   Given the CDC sheet says to immediately administer the vaccine after extracting it from the vial into the syringe  (https://www.cdc.gov/vaccines/covid-19/info-by-product/pfizer/downloads/prep-and-admin-summary.pdf) and here more than 10 syringes were filled and kept in a basket from which they were then used in a place where temperature may have been rising enough to exceed 77, I wasn't sure if that is acceptable in terms of timing and storing of the vaccines in sunlight on a warm window sill so I wanted to report what happened just in case this is acceptable or not and people receiving doses at this CVS are taken care of if needed.

I got my 1st Pfizer Covid-19 vaccination on 3/4/2021. No real adverse effects immediately - just a little sore right arm at the injection site and a watery, runny nose a day or so later that eventually stopped. I have allergies so I'm used to the runny nose symptom. However, on Monday evening, March 15, I noticed some slight pain where my lymph nodes are located underneath my jaw and close to my ear on the right side. There was a small lump that was tender to the touch, about the size of a small raisin or grape, under my jaw along my neck on the right side. To a much lesser extent, and barely noticeable, in a similar location, on my left side as well. I went to my primary care physician the next day, 3/16, who confirmed that I had swollen lymph nodes - and also told me they could notice them further down my neck as well, which I was not aware of previously. I had no other symptoms, e.g., no temperature, etc. They said that, yes, the swollen lymph nodes appeared to be consistent with earlier reports of swollen lymph nodes as a resulting side effect in some patients following a Covid19 vaccination, but also mentioned that often, this side effect was more noticeable several days after the vaccination. Since my swollen lymph nodes occurred nearly 10 days later, my PCP team said to go ahead and get the 2nd Pfizer vaccination as scheduled 3/25/21, but to return to their office two weeks later for another checkup to make sure there weren't any other issues going on.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient was advised to receive the vaccine regardless of an itchy throat with the first Pfizer Covid vaccine with some feeling like throat and tongue were swelling but EMTs on the scene administered IV benadryl with the first dose. With doctor recommendation to receive the second dose about 20 minutes after she received the second dose she started feeling her tongue have a fuzzy swelling sensation and began coughing frequently around 11 a.m.. Patient took 50 mg of Benadryl of her own immediately before the vaccine in order to counteract the same reaction from the first one. Due to increasing symptoms she received Epinephrine 0.3 mg/0.3 ml one shot at 11:09 a.m. and a second shot at 11:17 a.m. Patient began to show signs of improvement from the Epipen but not enough with one shot so she proceeded with the second one. She was able to leave the vaccine clinic to see her general practitioner that afternoon. She expressed that she felt jittery after the shots and we determined that the Benadryl liquid she had with her and took had Phenylephrine in it as well which combined with the Epinephrine was causing the shakiness. She felt stabilized but weak. Her blood pressure was 140/100 at 11:50 a.m. and 137/88 at 11:55 a.m.  Her allergist and general practitioner were contacted and notified of the incident and they instructed her further to use Benadryl tonight and to contact them tomorrow about any further concerns. She reported this evening at 5:27 p.m. that she was okay and did not have any further issues or the feelings of the allergic reaction.
LAB_DATA: No tests or labs were run.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: The vaccine appears to have been delivered subcutaneously, not IM as prescribed.  The  individual was short, stood behind me, and I did not feel the needle enter the muscle as I had during my first injection.  I assumed they were more skilled or I was more relaxed during the injection, so I didn't think anything of it.  The next day, there was a small bruise at the injection site and a raised red area emanating from the injection site anteriorly approximately 1 inch over the anterior deltoid.  The raised area could be palpated just under the skin and on top of the muscle and took nearly 2 weeks to resolve.  This was very different than my first vaccine injection experience approx. 3 weeks prior, when I felt the needle enter the middle deltoid muscle,  resulting in a round raised red area about the size of a quarter that felt deep in the muscle the next day, and which resolved in a few days.  No other signs or symptoms noted.     I called the  Health Department, as well as Pfizer to advise them of the incident and to request advice.  Both suggested filing a report but neither offered any advise other than to contact my MD, who also had no advice to offer.  Questions:  Given the temperature requirements of the Pfizer vaccine, and if it was not injected into the muscle, would a slower uptake  impact my immunity?  What is suggested to assess my current immunity status?  Might a booster shot may be indicated?  Any advice would be sincerely appreciated.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Received vaccine on March 3, no real issues, arm was slightly sore next day but nothing major - reaction as expected.  No issues past that until evening of March 12 I noticed slightly tenderness but didn't think much about it.  Next morning after a shower I notice my arm was red and still slightly tender.  Thought it might be due to shower so I went on about things and then looked later and realized it was still red and slightly warm to the touch.  By that evening it was much redder and took a temp gun to forehead and registered normal 98 but arm was 102.  That night I woke up and my tshirt was damp like I had had a sweat during the night. Next day still red and warm and same on Monday.  By Tuesday it seemed to be looking better - as I was expecting based off what I had been reading.  Wednesday it seemed like it was getting redder but more toward the edges of it, not so much in the center.  Now today the 18th, almost a week later, it is red all over and it has gotten bigger.  Before it was just more on the face of my upper arm but now it is extending all across the face and more toward the sides of my arm.  It doesn't itch, just red and warm.  I wasn't worried until now sense it seems the area is growing.  Like I said, it doesn't hurt or itch, just red and warm and area is larger now.

What initially appeared to be a slight glare, I later determined was an obscuration of the lower half of my vision in that eye which could be described as a clouding effect.  While disorienting and concerning, with closing/covering that eye, the problem slowly resolved itself. Within about 20 minutes, I had enough vision to comfortably and safely drive home. Another 20 minutes after that and the event had ended as far as I could tell.  I have never experienced anything like this in the past. Doing some (dangerous, I know) searching online, I discovered what it might be called and learned that there were some reports of similar events occurring with other vaccine recipients. Since I don't have a primary care physician, I'm hoping it is directly related to the vaccine and I hope it doesn't happen again with the second dose since my eyes are a critical part of my job.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient presented to the same vaccination site as she received 1st dose. She was guided to the Pfizer second dose documentation station, where the nurse documenting the vaccination did not heed the Epic alert that first dose was Moderna and Pfizer was being documented for 2nd dose.  Patient was directed to the Pfizer vaccine administration station and received Pfizer for dose 2 instead of Moderna.  The pharmacist in charge discovered an additional Moderna dose in inventory and discovered the potential error.  The pharmacist called the patient who described the events reported above and confirmed the error. The patient was educated that the current guidance is to not repeat dose 2 as both vaccines are mRNA vaccines.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: At 0700, a splotchy red rash appeared in my wrists and feet. It was not raised up and had an irregular border and was very very itchy. By 1000, the rash was splotchy up to my ankles and onto my forearm. By 1400, the entirety of my forearms were solid red rash, and I had large splotches on my calves, thighs, and upper arm. By 1800, the rash was only on my shoulder area, but lower body was still very red. My entire right leg from ankle to hip was red splotchy and my left leg from knee up. I had 2 splotches on my hips. I took 1 benadryl at this time and went to bed. I woke up on 3/18/21 with a few light splotches on my chest but no where else. This faded By 1000 and I do not have any rash now.

Around 1 am, I was sitting home watching tv and I started to smell blood coming from throat and I starting to feel like a blood chunk is coming out. And it happened. A medium sized blood chunk came out followed by couple small pieces of blood then I did drink lime mixed with water and stopped. But I still feel like there is something kind of blocking my throat a little bit.

After 24 hours of my vaccine at about 4pm the following day at my work, I started to feel like I was getting a cold, my face was hot. I went to the station to take my temperature, it was 98.4F and then I did a re-check 15 minutes later it was 97.2F. I was still feeling under the weather and left work a little before 5pm. I started to drive to the pharmacy when I got there I felt dizzy, I still went in and bought Tylenol cold and flu PM. When I got home, I still was feeling bad, I had severe headaches, migraines and also pain to base of my neck and my chest felt very heavy, like someone was sitting on top of me. I then went to bed early, was lying flat on my bed when I started to feel my heart, shaking my whole body. I felt really scared, these were strong palpitations. I then woke up around 3am, still having persistent headaches 10/10 pain level. I woke up because I could  not sleep and went to my living room, still having chest pain and pain in my neck with headaches that did not go away. My BP in the morning was high for me was 132/96, then 133/98 and at 730am it was 137/100 with a pulse of 80. I went to the emergency room where  I received IV medication, blood tests, triponents and EKG were performed which came back negative.  After an hour of my iv medication, I still continued with headaches, neck pain and my blood pressure was still high.  My doctor said that i had a severe reaction to the vaccine. I was discharged to go home after a few hours and I rested then I slowly started to fee better.
LAB_DATA: EKG, blood tests, triponents, all results were negative for these exams

Patient  came to the center for a Moderna vaccine at 5pm. The patient expressed that she felt dizzy shortly after immunization (before leaving the immunization chair). Her head began to fall backwards so I quickly supported the patient's head and neck area and was able to keep her from falling out of her chair. The patient fainted but regained consciousness approximately 3 seconds later. The patient came back alert but nauseous. The patient vomited in a trashcan and then felt fine. The patient blamed the reaction on her severe anxiety and said the exact same thing happened after a nose piercing. I observed the patient for 30 minutes and sent her on her way. The patient left healthy and happy. I told the patient to warn the pharmacist prior to receiving her second dose. No drugs were administered. Written up in SCRT and VAERS. I followed up with the patient at 7 pm and she was home safe.

Pt has history of anaphylactic allergic reaction (not to vaccine or contraindicated material), made aware of risk (was told she would have to stay 30 minutes) and decided to be vaccinated. Approximately 20-25 minutes after her vaccination, she mentioned to the living facility manager that she wasn't feeling well. I checked her blood pressure (142/111) and pulse (82) at 8:27am. She said that was elevated for her and she felt as though she was having difficulty breathing. I had the living facility staff member call 911. At 8:29, I proceeded to help the patient self inject in her right upper leg with a generic epipen (this was her preference since she has used before) - I added with counting to 10. I then gave her 50mg diphenhydramine IM in her left upper arm (Moderna injection was in right upper arm). Within 1-2 minutes, she said that she could tell the epipen was working and helping her to breathe more easily. At 8:34am, I took her blood pressure (148/111) and pulse (90). By 8:38am, she said she was starting to struggle to breath again. Per the pharmacy emergencey protocol, epipen can be given again in 10-20 minutes. At 10 minutes, since she still said her breathing was getting more difficult and the EMS had not arrived, she was given a second dose of a generic epipen in the left upper leg. EMS arrived 2-3 minutes later and was provided with all above information. Follow up phone call with doctor at the emergency department, said that she was monitored for an hour and then sent home. He advised that she not get the second Moderna shot or if determined necessary by her PCP to get it in a doctor's office setting.

Pt had history of asthma and frequent nebulizer use and had it in car with her for drive-thru vaccine clinic we did at location, which has a large parking lot. We gave 80 doses. About 5 minutes later in car parking lot she started to use her personal nebulizer. I saw her in passenger side of car using a personal nebulizer so I talked to her and her daughter to find out what was going on. They said she has exacerbations all the time and this was not out of ordinary for her. I checked pulse ox and did a lung exam, etc, and she was stable.  She seemed baseline according to history by her and her daughter.  As she seemed at baseline and clinically was comfortable and conversant whole time, and she felt better after her nebulizer, I told them to have a low threshold for going to ER or calling 911 if her asthma was worse or different than her usual symptoms.  They agreed. According to daughter, she did well until about 24 hours the next day. The daughter said she was fine and she went to store and when she returned EMTs were intubating patient and apparently the patient used her epipen and called 911 herself. I have never had a wart or boil before in 75 years.  I feared the risk of sepsis to my bilateral hip joint replacements.  It seemed like the mRNA vaccine was commanding all of my antibody formation and leaving nothing in my immune system to address routine small bacterial intrusions. Patient has family history of VTE (father died of PE, mother had DVTs and was on warfarin). Patient was admitted from 3/6-3/7, discharged on apixaban. ID consult placed, ID physician recommended patient receive 2nd dose of COVID-19 vaccine in 21 days as scheduled.

Positive COVID test/hospitalization after COVID vaccine Narrative: Patient received 1st dose of Moderna COVID-19 vaccine on 2/11/2021. Patient then presented to the ED on 2/20/21 where he tested COVID positive and reported that his onset of symptoms was around 2/17/2021. Patient had increasing oxygen requirements and was transferred to the MICU. Patient then had to be intubated on 2/28/21. On that day, he was started on dexamethasone 6mg x10days. He was not given remdesivir due to his late presentation following symptom onset. His hospital course was further complicated by AKI which resolved and superimposed MSSA pneumonia as well as MSSA bacteremia. He was extubated on 3/7 and was discharged on 3/12 to the COVID rehab unit. He received his 2nd Moderna COVID-19 vaccine 3/12/21 without issue.
